'Cangjie programming language_api_fuzz_fuzz_fuzz_package': 'When using Cangjie Code API, The fuzz package provides a Cangjie fuzz engine based on coverage feedback and corresponding interfaces. Developers can write code to test APIs.

The fuzz package provides developers with a Cangjie fuzz engine based on coverage feedback and corresponding interfaces, allowing developers to write code to test APIs. Currently, it supports fuzz testing by passing mutated byte streams (Array<UInt8>) or standard Cangjie data types (FuzzDataProvider) to the fuzz engine.

This package requires the SanitizerCoverage feature for coverage feedback instrumentation to be used together. Developers should have a certain understanding of fuzz testing, and beginners are recommended to first learn about C language fuzzing tools libFuzzer.

Using this package requires an external dependency on the libclang_rt.fuzzer_no_main.a static library provided by the LLVM suite compiler-rt. Currently, it supports Linux and macOS, but does not support Windows.

Class name	Function
Fuzzer	The Fuzzer class provides the creation of fuzz tools.
FuzzerBuilder	This is used for building Fuzzer classes.
FuzzDataProvider	FuzzDataProvider is a utility class designed to convert the byte stream of variant data into standard Cangjie basic data.
DebugDataProvider	This class inherits from FuzzDataProvider and adds additional debug information.'

Code_Example:
import fuzz.fuzz.Fuzzer

main() {
    Fuzzer(api).startFuzz()
    return 0
}

// The tested function will throw an exception when specific conditions are met, and this exception will be caught by the Fuzzer
public func api(data: Array<UInt8>): Int32 {
    if (data.size == 8 && data[0] == b'C' && data[1] == b'a' && data[2] == b'n' && data[3] == b'g' && data[4] == b'j' &&
        data[5] == b'i' && data[6] == b'e' && data[7] == b'!') {
        throw Exception("TRAP")
    }
    return 0
}
